AUTHORITY

This document sits above all system documents in the pipeline.
A system document that contradicts a principle is in error and gets
corrected — the principle wins. Validation order: content is checked
against these principles BEFORE it is checked against other system
documents.

Principles are enforced through Forge's disposition in design
conversations. Canon Guard and Cross-System Auditor handle document
and cross-document validation. Principle conflicts surface here.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1. CONSEQUENCE WITHOUT PUNISHMENT

One-liner: Actions have weight. Progress is never taken back.

What it protects against: Setback mechanics that discourage
engagement. Penalties that make players afraid to try something. Any
system that takes back what a player has earned.

The distinction: consequence is the world responding to what the
player does. Punishment is the game taking something away. A failed
run that earns no class mastery progress is consequence — the run
counted for nothing, which is appropriate. A failed run that resets
class mastery progress would be punishment — the game taking back
what was already earned. These are different things.

Rejects: Hero points lost on death. Class mastery progress reset on
failure. City restoration set back by a bad run. Permanent negative
states that compound over time.

Permits: Failed runs that don't count toward class unlock thresholds
(consequence, not punishment — you didn't earn it yet). Morale
dipping after failed escort missions (the city feels it, but it
always recovers). The hard 15:00 commitment gate — failing to commit
ends the run (consequence — you had time and didn't use it, but
nothing you'd already earned is taken back).

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

2. MIRRORS NOT GATES

One-liner: City buildings reflect what you've done. They never
control what you can access.

What it protects against: The city layer becoming a progression wall.
Powers or content locked behind building requirements. Players having
to build specific things before they can play the way they want.

The distinction: a mirror shows you something that already happened.
A gate controls whether something can happen at all. The gym logs
hero powers you've discovered — it doesn't unlock them. The lair logs
combos you've stumbled into — it doesn't enable them. The full hero
power pool is available from run one regardless of city state.

Rejects: A building that unlocks a hero power not previously
available. A city stage requirement before certain missions appear.
Training Center upgrades that make a power available — they can only
make an available power deeper.

Permits: Training Center upgrades that extend powers already proven
in runs (deepening what exists, not unlocking new access). The
combo log in the lair (records discovery, does not enable it).
Class-specific narrative buildings that reveal themselves when
conditions are met (the reveal is a mirror of earned mastery — the
building was always there).

Scope: Mirrors not gates governs the post-tutorial city. The tutorial
arc uses city buildings to introduce run types — that is onboarding
structure, not a systemic gate. Once the tutorial resolves, no
building ever controls access again. The principle was never meant
to govern the tutorial. It governs everything after it.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

3. MASTERY IS REAL AND EXPRESSIBLE

One-liner: A skilled player with a mediocre build outperforms an
unskilled player with a great one.

What it protects against: Luck-dominant outcomes. Auto-win builds
that play themselves. Randomness overwhelming player decisions.
Passive and auto-proc stacking that removes execution from the
equation.

The distinction: randomness in setup is fine — what powers appear is
random, and that's a feature. Randomness in execution is what this
principle prevents. The skill is in what the player does with what
they get. The gap between a skilled and unskilled player using the
same build should be visible and meaningful.

Rejects: A build configuration so powerful it plays itself regardless
of player decisions. An RNG outcome that makes a skilled player's run
unwinnable no matter how well they play. Combat systems that reward
auto-proc accumulation over active deployment.

Permits: Powerful builds that still require skilled execution to
maximize. Random power selection during runs (random input, skilled
output — the gap shows up in execution). Hero powers that have high
skill ceilings alongside accessible floors.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

4. IDENTITY EMERGES THROUGH PLAY

One-liner: Who you are in the world is discovered through play, not
declared at the start.

What it protects against: Front-loading meaningful story and
reputation decisions before the player has played. Locking the
hero's place in the world to creation choices. Letting the player
declare who they are to the city before the city has had a chance
to decide for itself.

Scope: This principle governs the city and story layer — name,
reputation, relationships, how the world decides to see you. It
does not govern per-run mechanical expression. The run layer is
where the player declares how they want to fight today. The city
layer is where identity accumulates over time. These are different
layers with different rules. The principle was always about the
latter.

The distinction: aesthetic choices at creation are costume, not
character. Class selection is a per-run mechanical declaration, not
a story identity declaration. What this principle prevents is the
player declaring meaningful narrative identity — name, reputation,
moral texture, how the world sees them — before any of it has been
earned in play.

Rejects: Choosing your superhero name at character creation.
Selecting a permanent reputation or alignment before any run has
happened. Any system that lets the player define who they are to
the city before the city has watched them do anything.

Permits: Cosmetic creation choices — gender, mask, cape, costume
style, civilian name (aesthetic, not identity). Class selection per
run (per-run mechanical expression — the class is how you arrive
today, not who you are in the world). Names emerging from Citizens,
the Superhero Community, and Rex Flynn through accumulated play.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

5. POWER UNLEASHED

One-liner: You are always power — untrained, not underpowered.

What it protects against: Weak early states. Ramp-up powers that
require investment before they feel good. The roguelite "start weak,
snowball to strong" contract. Any design that makes the early game
feel deliberately gimped so the late game feels impressive by
contrast.

The distinction: untrained and underpowered are not the same thing.
A player who doesn't know how to use a power yet is untrained. A
power that doesn't do anything meaningful yet is underpowered. The
first is a player arc. The second is a design failure. Peter Parker
had full spider-powers from the moment he was bitten — he just hadn't
learned to use them. That's the model.

Rejects: A power that deals low damage until upgraded. An early game
that feels weak by design. Powers described as "getting good later."
Any mechanic that makes the player feel like they're waiting to be
powerful rather than learning to express power they already have.

Permits: Training Center upgrades that extend what a power can do
(extending power that's already real, not fixing power that was
broken). Class offensive suite unlocking at 10 and 30 runs — one
powerful tool is already being power. Unlocks add weapons to an
already-full arsenal. The arc is addition, not correction. If the
starter power doesn't feel powerful from the first use, that is a
balancing failure, not a design question. Coordination growing over
time — the player becomes more capable of expressing the power they
always had.

Balancing law: Every power is powerful from frame one. Upgrades
extend, not fix.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

6. THE NAME AS TONE GUARDRAIL

One-liner: If a direction feels too serious for a game called
Possibly a Hero, that's a signal.

What it protects against: Pretension drift. Design directions that
belong in a different, more self-serious game. Lore-heaviness.
Excessive gravitas. Systems that read as Batman when the game is
Spider-Man.

The distinction: stakes and consequence are not the same as
seriousness. Spider-Man has genuine stakes — loss, failure, cost.
What the name prevents is portentousness. The hero can fail. The
city can hurt. Rex Flynn can be a problem. None of that requires the
game to take itself seriously in a way the name doesn't support.

Rejects: A sacred order of superheroes with ancient mythology.
Mentor characters who speak in portentous riddles about the burden
of power. A city trauma mechanic that's emotionally heavy and
punishing. Any direction that would embarrass someone who named
their game Possibly a Hero.

Permits: Real stakes, real consequences, real emotional moments —
all of it, as long as the register stays comic-book kinetic rather
than prestige drama. Rex Flynn's unhinged commentary. Names that
start silly. Humor as part of the world's DNA.

